  <div id="grooming" class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="Grooming: The Wiry Coat and the Famous Beard" imageAlt="Miniature Schnauzer puppy having its beard combed during grooming" imageSrc={imgScene3} imagePosition="left">
      <p>The Schnauzer coat is low-shedding but not low-maintenance. Plan on brushing 2 to 3 times a week, a clip at the groomer every 4 to 6 weeks to keep the pet coat tidy, and, the part nobody warns you about, daily beard duty. That handsome beard collects water, food and adventure, and a quick comb and wipe after meals keeps it from smelling like everything it's been dipped in.</p>
      <p>In our humidity, keep the body coat clipped short and the furnishings (legs and beard) combed through so they never mat. The grooming tools to start are all in your starter kit, and we'll show you the beard routine on delivery day.</p>
    </CaptionedBlock>
  </div>

  <CloudDivider fillClass="fill-[var(--color-mint-100)]" />
  <div id="health" class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="Miniature Schnauzer Health: What We Check Before You Take One Home" imageAlt="Miniature Schnauzer puppy at a veterinary health check before going home" imageSrc={imgScene4} variant="mid">
      <p>Every Miniature Schnauzer goes home vet-checked, vaccinated, dewormed, and microchipped. The Schnauzer health points worth knowing: the breed handles dietary fat poorly, with pancreatitis and high blood fats (hyperlipidaemia) its best-known risks, so the feeding rules below are genuinely important; bladder stones occur more often than in most breeds, and generous fresh water every day is the cheap insurance; and eye conditions such as cataracts appear in some lines, worth a look at any adult dog's eyes you're shown.</p>
      <p>Feeding is simple: your puppy comes with the food it is already eating, and any change should be gradual over a week. For portioning guidance see the <a href="/learn/puppy-health/" class="underline underline-offset-2 text-[var(--color-accent-hover)]">puppy health checks explained</a> guide.</p>
    </CaptionedBlock>
  </div>
  <CloudDivider fillClass="fill-[var(--color-mint-100)]" flip />

  <div class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="The Schnauzer Diet Rule: Boring Food Is a Feature" imagePosition="none" variant="card">
      <p>If you remember one breed-specific fact from this page, make it this: Miniature Schnauzers and fatty food don't mix. The breed is unusually prone to pancreatitis, a painful and dangerous inflammation usually triggered by rich, oily meals, the char siu end of the dinner table, festive leftovers, anything fried.</p>
      <p>The rule in practice: measured portions of its regular food, treats under ten percent of the day's intake, and a family agreement that nobody feeds from the table, however good the beard-and-eyebrows begging performance is. It is a genuinely excellent performance. Hold the line anyway.</p>
      <div slot="side" class="clay h-full bg-[var(--color-peach-100)] p-6 sm:p-8">
        <p class="text-xs font-bold uppercase text-[var(--color-cream-500)]" style="letter-spacing: 0.08em;">Feeding rules</p>
        <ul class="mt-4 space-y-3">
          {[
            'No fatty or oily human food, ever',
            'Measured meals with the kit\'s feeding cup',
            'Fresh water always, to protect against bladder stones',
